TY  - JOUR
T1  - Modeling a Paradigm Shift: From Producer Innovation to User and Open Collaborative Innovation
AU  - Baldwin, Carliss
AU  - von Hippel, Eric
Y1  - 2011/03/11
PY  - 2011
DA  - 2011/12/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/orsc.1100.0618
DO  - 10.1287/orsc.1100.0618
T2  - Organization Science
JF  - Organization Science
JO  - Organization Science
SP  - 1399
EP  - 1417
VL  - 22
IS  - 6
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - In this paper, we assess the economic viability of innovation by producers relative to two increasingly important alternative models: innovations by single-user individuals or firms and open collaborative innovation. We analyze the design costs and architectures and communication costs associated with each model. We conclude that both innovation by individual users and open collaborative innovation increasingly compete with and may displace producer innovation in many parts of the economy. We explain why this represents a paradigm shift with respect to innovation research, policy making, and practice. We discuss important implications and offer suggestions for further research.
AB  - In this paper, we assess the economic viability of innovation by producers relative to two increasingly important alternative models: innovations by single-user individuals or firms and open collaborative innovation. We analyze the design costs and architectures and communication costs associated with each model. We conclude that both innovation by individual users and open collaborative innovation increasingly compete with and may displace producer innovation in many parts of the economy. We explain why this represents a paradigm shift with respect to innovation research, policy making, and practice. We discuss important implications and offer suggestions for further research.
